definition.value: A hydrochloride obtained by combining (1R,2S)-tranylcypromine with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining (1S,2R)-tranylcypromine with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the primary amino function of (1R,2S)-tranylcypromine.
A nitrosamine that is dipropylamine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen has been replaced by a nitroso group. It is a genotoxic carcinogen, targeting the lung, liver, thyroid, and kidney.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the primary amino function of (1S,2R)-tranylcypromine.
An O-acylcarnitine that is carnitine having a hexadecenedioyl group as the acyl substituent (position of the double bond is unspecified).
A pyrimidine nucleotide-sugar having thymine as the nucleobase and 4-(methylamino)-2,3,4,6-tetradeoxy-alpha-D-glucose as the sugar component.
A hydrate that is the hexahydrate form of manganese(II) sulfate.
A hydrate that is the pentahydrate form of manganese(II) sulfate.
A poly(hydroxybutyrate) composed of repeating (R)-3-hydroxybutyryl units.
A potassium salt that is the dipotassium salt of carbonic acid.
A potassium salt that is the dipotassium salt of phosphoric acid.
An A-type aurachin that is quinoline N-oxide which is substituted by a methyl group at position 2, a hydroxy group at position 3, and a triprenyl group at position 4.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining pyridoxal with one molar equivalent of hydrochloric acid.
A pyridinium ion obtained by protonation of the ring nitrogen of pyridoxal.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining pyridoxamine with one molar equivalent of hydrochloric acid. Used for treatment of diabetic nephropathy.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining pyridoxamine with two molar equivalents of hydrochloric acid. Used for treatment of diabetic nephropathy.
A pyridinium ion obtained by protonation of both nitrogens of pyridoxamine.
A ceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of henicosanoic acid with the amino group of 14-methylhexadecasphingosine. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
An N-acyl-15-methylhexadecasphing-4-enine in which the acyl group has 26 carbons and 1 double bond. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
An N-acyl-15-methylhexadecasphing-4-enine in which the acyl group has 25 carbons and 1 double bond. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

An L-alanyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-alanine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
An L-arginyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-arginine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
An L-asparaginyl derivative that is the ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-asparagine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
An L-aspartic acid derivative that is the ester obtained by formal condensation of the alpha-carboxy group of L-aspartic acid with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
An L-cysteinyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-cysteine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
An L-methionine derivative that is the ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-formyl-L-methionine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.

Any steroid substituted by a formyl group.
An L-histidine derivative that is the ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-histidine with the 3'-hydroxy group of AMP.
